Introduction

Twitch.tv is a popular live-streaming platform owned by Amazon that was originally made for gamers to live-stream themselves playing video games. In recent years it has expanded its audience to more than gamers with the addition of streaming categories such as "Just Chatting" and "Talk Shows & Podcasts." This data set contains analytics for Twitch's top 1000 channels taken over a year. The data used is available here. In this tutorial, we will go through the steps of: Data Collection, Data Clean Up, Data Exploration, Outlier Removal, and Predicition and Machine Learning using Regression! Our goal is to attempt to predict total Followers Gained over a year using the columns in the dataset.

We are pulling the data from a CVS file downloaded from the link above.

Data Clean Up ¶

The column names have inconsistent capitalizing and naming conventions. We are changing them to help with structure and organization. We are also dropping the "Partnered," "Mature," and "Langauge" columns as they are not relevant to what we are looking at, and in the "Partnered" case, the majority was "yes," which would create artificial outliers in the dataset. Then we want to make sure we don't have any missing values in the dataset.

In [ ]:
# Rename colums to make typing and readibility easier
df = df.rename(columns = {"Watch time(Minutes)": "Watch_Time", "Stream time(minutes)": "Stream_Time", 
                          "Followers gained": "Followers_Gained", "Peak viewers": "Peak_Viewers", 
                          "Average viewers": "Average_Viewers", "Views gained": "Views_Gained"})
# Drop Partnered, Mature, and Language Columns as they are not relevent to what we are looking for
df = df.drop(columns = {"Partnered", "Mature", "Language"})

Outlier Removal ¶

It is clear from the graphs above that many outliers are making the data unreadable, and hard to predict. We are going to rescope our data frame but cutting out the large outliers and looking at where the data is most populated.

We are achieving this by filtering the database with cutoffs determined by the graphs above. Our goal is to have the clustered bulk of the data shown in the graphs above be the main representation of the predictions.

This resulted in a reduction of 335 rows. This number is high when compared to the starting 1000 rows, but it is necessary as much of the data set are outliers.

In [ ]:
# From the first plot, remove outlier Average Viewers and cut down on time spent streaming
df = df[df.Average_Viewers < 7000]
df = df[df.Stream_Time < 250000]

# From the scond graph, cut down Watch time and Followers Gained
df = df[df.Watch_Time < 600000000]
df = df[df.Followers_Gained < 450000]

# From the third graph cut downb Peak Viewers
df = df[df.Peak_Viewers < 60000]

# From the fourth graph cut off Views gained
df = df[df.Views_Gained < 20000000]

Predicition and Machine Learning using Regression! ¶

The first thing we are going to do is look for features worth dropping due to a high P-Value or multicollinearity that may exist. A high P-Value indicates that the feature is not strong enough to suggest an effect exists in the population. Multicollinearity is when correlated features are correlated to each other. This is an issue because some regression models, such as linear, will perform worse when having to deal with multicollinearity.

In [ ]:
# seperate the independent and dependent variables
X = df.drop(["Channel", "Followers_Gained"], axis = "columns") 
y = df["Followers_Gained"]

# To start we are going to use Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) to help us determine 
# if we have multicollinearity which may hurt our regression results.   
model = sm.OLS(y, X)
fitModel = model.fit()
print(fitModel.summary())

To both look for multicollinearity and check the P-Values of our features, we are using Statsmodel's Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) regression model. We can see above in the notes section it is suggesting there exists a multicollinearity issue. We can tell there is multicollinearity because the standard error and condition number is a high value for some of the features, in particular, Watch_Time. On top of that, we can see the P-Value for Views_Gained is 0.6, which is a much higher value than we want to see, which means it is also a feature we should be looking to drop.

In [ ]:
# seperate the independent and dependent variables as well as drop the unwanted variables
X = df.drop(["Channel", "Followers_Gained", "Watch_Time", "Views_Gained"], axis = "columns") 
y = df["Followers_Gained"]

# Create the training and testing sets where the test set is 25% of the data.
# Random state is set to allow for reproducable training and test sets. 
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.25, random_state = 50)

Now that we have decided which features we want to drop and which ones to keep. We separate our independent and dependent variables. While doing this, we can drop our unwanted features, such as Watch_Time. Next, we separated our independent and dependent sets into a training and test set using SKLearn's train_test_split. Doing this, we took 75% of the data and kept it as the training set and put the other 25% into a test set.

Next, we will move on to predicting followers gained. To do this, we will start with linear regression, as it is the simplest of the regression models. Since we removed the multicollinearity, it will likely perform better than if we did not. Unlike the next two regression algorithms, linear regression struggles to deal with many correlated independent variables.

In [ ]:
# Start with linear regression
# Linear regression has no hyperparameters to tune
linear = LinearRegression().fit(X_train, y_train)
scores_train = cross_val_score(linear, X_train, y_train, cv = 10)
scores_test = cross_val_score(linear, X_test, y_test, cv = 10)
print("Training set average 10-fold cross validation score (R Squared):", scores_train.mean())
print("Test set average 10-fold cross validation score (R Squared):", scores_test.mean())

# To use mean squared error make a prediction on the test set 
y_predicted = linear.predict(X_test)
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predicted)
print("Mean Squared Error of the test set:", mse)

Training set average 10-fold cross validation score (R Squared): 0.2417396472901107
Test set average 10-fold cross validation score (R Squared): 0.15853877536592628
Mean Squared Error of the test set: 7220376279.757099

Linear regression is the only regression model we will be using that does not require any form of hyperparameter tuning. With that being said, we can fit our model using the training set. Then we can use SKLearn's cross_val_score to do a 10-fold cross-validation on both the training and test set. As you can see above, our model did not perform well, with about 24.2% accuracy on the training set and only 15.9% accuracy on the test set. This shows that our model is likely to overfit due to the test set performing poorly compared to the training set. Next, we will show the mean squared error for the model, but we cannot interpret that number until we can compare it to that of our other models.

With that being said, let's move on to Ridge regression, as it is a regularised regression algorithm and will deal with correlated independent variables better than linear regression will. On top of that, regularised regression algorithms tend to do a better job of not overfitting.

In [ ]:
# It is best practice when using a regularised regression to scale your independent variables.
# However, our data is all large numbers so in this case we do not need to do this. 

# Create the default Ridge model 
ridge = Ridge()

# Tune Hyperparameters for Ridge regression using a Grid Search Cross Validation
# Alpha is the only hyperparameter
grid = {"alpha" : [float(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 0.01, stop = 100, num = 50)]}
tuned_ridge = GridSearchCV(estimator = ridge, param_grid = grid, cv = 10, verbose = 1, n_jobs = 4)
tuned_ridge.fit(X_train, y_train)
print("Best alpha value:", tuned_ridge.best_params_)
print("Highest score (R Squared) on the training set when attempting to tune our alpha value:", tuned_ridge.best_score_)

# use cross_val_score to get the cross validation score of the test and training sets
scores_train = cross_val_score(tuned_ridge.best_estimator_, X_train, y_train, cv = 10)
scores_test = cross_val_score(tuned_ridge.best_estimator_, X_test, y_test, cv = 10)
print("Training set average 10-fold cross validation score (R Squared):", scores_train.mean())
print("Test set average 10-fold cross validation score (R Squared):", scores_test.mean())

# To use mean squared error make a prediction on the test set
y_predicted = tuned_ridge.best_estimator_.predict(X_test)
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predicted)
print("Mean Squared Error of the test set:", mse)

Ridge regression is our first model that requires hyperparameter tuning. It only has one hyperparameter to tune, called alpha. To tune it, we are going to use SKLearn's GridSearchCV. We are picking 50 evenly spaced values between 0.01 and 100.0, and GridSearchCV will do a 10-fold cross-validation on all those different alpha values to determine which one causes our model to perform the best on our training set. The default value for alpha is 1, so to test out the two extremes on the opposite sides of 1, I chose 0.01 and 100. In the end, our ridge regression model ended up performing extremely similarly to linear regression. Both of them scored 24.2% accuracy on the training set and 15.9% accuracy on the test set. Using mean squared error, the ridge regression performed worse than the linear regression getting a higher score by 0.22.

Next are also going to try out lasso regression which is another regularised regression algorithm similar to ridge regression.

Lasso regression is fairly similar to ridge regression in the sense that they are both regularised, and they both have a single hyperparameter alpha that needs to be tuned. Since lasso's alpha value also defaults to 1, we are going to use the same alpha values to test in the GridSearchCV as we did for ridge regression. Also similar to ridge regression, our lasso model scored 24.2% accuracy on the training set and 15.9% accuracy on the test set. However, where lasso differs, it is scored decently worse on mean squared error than linear and ridge regression by about 876. This means, overall, it is a less accurate model than our linear and ridge models.

Linear, Lasso, and Ridge regression all scored very similarly when using R Squared and Mean Squared Error. In hopes of finding a more accurate model, we are going to try a random forest regression algorithm.

In [ ]:
# Create the default random forest regression model 
rf = RandomForestRegressor() 

# Hyperparm tuning  
n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 5, stop = 150, num = 10)]
max_depth = [2, 3]
min_samples_split = [2, 5]
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2]
max_features = ["auto", "log2"]
bootstrap = [True, False]

# make the dictionary 
grid = {"n_estimators" : n_estimators, "max_depth" : max_depth, "min_samples_split" : min_samples_split, 
        "min_samples_leaf" : min_samples_leaf, "max_features" : max_features, "bootstrap" : bootstrap}

# Tune hyperparameters using Sklearn's GridSearchCV with 4-fold cross validation.
# We are doing less folds compared to lasso and ridge regression because we have more 
# hyperparameters to tune meaning it would take a significant amount of time to do 10 folds. 
tuned_rf = GridSearchCV(estimator = rf, param_grid = grid, cv = 4, verbose = 1, n_jobs = 1) 
tuned_rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
print("Best hyperparameter values:", tuned_rf.best_params_)
# use cross_val_score to get the cross validation score of the test and training sets
scores_train = cross_val_score(tuned_rf.best_estimator_, X_train, y_train, cv = 10)
scores_test = cross_val_score(tuned_rf.best_estimator_, X_test, y_test, cv = 10)
print("Training set average 10-fold cross validation score (R Squared):", scores_train.mean())
print("Test set average 10-fold cross validation score (R Squared):", scores_test.mean())

# To use mean squared error make a prediction on the test set
y_predicted = tuned_rf.best_estimator_.predict(X_test)
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predicted)
print("Mean Squared Error of the test set:", mse)

Mean Squared Error of the test set: 6394655411.503981

Since our linear, ridge, and lasso regression models have all performed poorly, we are moving on to random forest regression. Random forest regression has considerably more hyperparameters compared to ridge and lasso. We are going to be tuning 6 of them, with n_estimators being the most important to test multiple values with. n_estimators is the number of decision trees this random forest uses. Most of the hyperparameters we are testing in the GridSearchCV are the default and another value. We are only doing 4-fold cross-validation when tuning because tuning this many parameters takes a considerably higher amount of time compared to ridge and lasso regression. None of the models we tested have been particularly accurate. However, the Random Forest Regression model is the most accurate one. It scored 28.6% accuracy on the training set and 30.6% accuracy on the test set. Not only that, but its mean square error was 825,720,868 points lower than that of our next lowest mean square error (linear regression).

Now that we have found our most accurate, though still pretty inaccurate model, we are going to show the distribution of followers gained compared to our prediction using the random forest regression model on all our data sets.

Conclusion ¶

Despite trying multiple different regression algorithms and cutting out harmful data, we were never able to come up with an accurate model for predicting Twitch streamers' follower growth. We hypothesize this is due to there being external factors that affect follower growth that is not captured within the data set. An example of this is whether a channel has Twitch Drops enabled (viewers get free content for the game by watching the streamer), which would artificially inflate viewing numbers as people watch the stream for the in-game loot they would receive and not because they like the streamer. Machine learning is not perfect, the algorithms cannot create connections that don't exist. That is not to be discouraging, some variables won't be able to be predicted accurately, but it is a Data Scientist's job to explore the data and try to find the connections. Also, just because we weren't able to predict Follower growth with this dataset doesn't mean it can't be predicted in the future. To get a more accurate prediction, we could assemble a larger dataset that has more features than the one we were using. Regardless of the result, this tutorial has shown you the steps to clean, organize, plot, and apply machine learning algorithms to whatever projects you have in mind, hopefully with more success.
